<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/78308CAA-8483-45C0-A280-0AB4B6AD9D35"><gtr:id>78308CAA-8483-45C0-A280-0AB4B6AD9D35</gtr:id><gtr:name>Medical Research Council</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Polaris House</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>North Star Avenue</gtr:line2><gtr:postCode>SN2 1FL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South West</gtr:region></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/78308CAA-8483-45C0-A280-0AB4B6AD9D35"><gtr:id>78308CAA-8483-45C0-A280-0AB4B6AD9D35</gtr:id><gtr:name>Medical Research Council</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Polaris House</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>North Star Avenue</gtr:line2><gtr:postCode>SN2 1FL</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South West</gtr:region></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/D70DF3E3-F850-4FFA-AAF7-5BAD47327773"><gtr:id>D70DF3E3-F850-4FFA-AAF7-5BAD47327773</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Marta</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Joanna</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Buszewicz</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_U122788474"><gtr:id>D2C6A88D-4C98-4617-B5A9-3A306C0540DC</gtr:id><gtr:title>Evaluation of a system of structured, pro-active care for chronic depression in primary care (ProCEED)</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_U122788474</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Depression is very common affecting 5-10% of people in the UK. A substantial proportion of these people will have chronic depressive disorders. The health and social costs of this are considerable. We know that people with chronic depression form a socially disadvantaged and marginalised group because of the effects of their disorder on their health and social functioning. The ProCEED study aims to determine whether structured care of patients with chronic depression leads to a cost-effective improvement in medical and social outcomes for patients when compared with the usual GP care patients receive. This study will involve over 400 patients from 40 GP practices throughout the UK.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Depression is very common, affecting 5-10% of people in the UK and it is the third most common reason for GP consultations. Between 18-25% of patients will have chronic depressive disorders. The health and social costs of this are considerable. In the year 2000, the total cost of adult depression in the UK was estimated at over 9 billion pounds, the majority of these costs were due to indirect or social costs. People with chronic depression form a socially disadvantaged and marginalised group because of the effects of their disorder on their health and social functioning and the lack of services targeting their needs. Despite national programmes to raise public awareness there still appears to be reluctance among both the public and health practitioners to recognise depression as a disorder where medical, psychological and social interventions can be of benefit. Studies from the USA have shown that organised, enhanced care can have a beneficial effect on the outcomes of patients with acute major depression, as well as those with high risk of recurrence. These strategies have not been formally researched in the UK.

The aims of the trial are:
To establish whether structured pro active care of patients with chronic depression in primary care leads to a cost-effective improvement in medical and social outcomes when compared with usual GP care. 
To assess whether training general practice nurses leads to improved assessment and follow-up of patients.
To increase the understanding of inequalities in health care for people with chronic depression.

This is a randomised controlled trial, comparing &amp;quot;GP usual care&amp;quot; (control group) with a &amp;quot;structured care&amp;quot; (intervention group) approach, involving regular follow-up of the patients by the practice nurse in addition to their usual GP care. Patients over 18 years of age with two or more episodes of depression within the previous 3 years will be eligible to participate. We aim to recruit 424 patients overall from 40 GPRF practices throughout the UK. 
This study is funded by the Big Lottery and is a collaboration between MIND, UCL Primary care and population sciences department and the MRCGPRF.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-04-25</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>317038</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>380000</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Big Lottery Research Awards</gtr:description><gtr:end>2011-07-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Big Lottery Fund</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:fundingRef>RG/1/010166750.</gtr:fundingRef><gtr:id>D3A05F09-6081-40E7-8FE6-6C2C881CE7CE</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>HSiJDVnquMf</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Charity/Non Profit</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2007-04-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>EC092F4C-B2DA-400C-A1A4-D3C040EB6F2A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Structured pro-active care for chronic depression by practice nurses in primary care: a qualitative evaluation.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>PloS one</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/9deaa0225